    <fr:anchor>1267</fr:anchor>
    <fr:addr type="user">FA-000T</fr:addr>
    <fr:route>FA-000T.xml</fr:route>
    <fr:title text="Orthonormal sequence">Orthonormal sequence</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors>
      <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
    </fr:authors>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>An orthonormal sequence in a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is a sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(u_n)]]></fr:tex> of vectors in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> such that:</fr:p>
    <fr:p>1. Each vector has unit norm: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||u_n|| = 1]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>2. Different vectors are orthogonal to each other: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u_m, u_n \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m \neq  n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>Equivalently, an orthonormal sequence satisfies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u_m, u_n \rangle  = \delta _{mn}]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{mn}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0011.xml" addr="FA-0011" title="Kronecker delta">Kronecker delta</fr:link>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>An orthonormal sequence is a fundamental concept in the study of Hilbert spaces and forms the basis for Fourier analysis and many approximation methods.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:backmatter>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
